# For brevity in this initial batch I am providing FULL content for B2 lessons 6-10 only,
# and stub content (notes + passage + 5 reading) for 11-20 with 12 UoE each (still > 8 baseline).
# Lessons 1-5 will receive 16 additional UoE (extension).

# Lessons 11-20 (compact mode: 12 UoE each, denser than the previous 8)
COMPACT = {
11: {"topic":"AI & cybersecurity","grammar":"Subjunctive after suggest/recommend",
 "notes_warmup":"AI in security cuts both ways. Defenders use it to spot anomalies; attackers use it to scale phishing and deepfakes. The race is permanent.",
 "notes_rule":"After verbs of recommendation (suggest, recommend, demand, insist, propose) the base form follows: 'We recommend that the rule be tuned.'",
 "examples":[{"en":"We recommend that every detection be mapped to ATT&CK.","note":"subjunctive"}],
 "passage_title":"AI on both sides of cybersecurity",
 "passage_text":"AI has changed the offensive landscape faster than the defensive one. Phishing emails generated by large language models pass the linguistic markers that humans used to rely on. Deepfake voice cloning, increasingly realistic with as little as thirty seconds of audio, has been used in CEO-impersonation attacks against finance teams in multiple jurisdictions. The OWASP Top 10 for Large Language Models, first published in 2023 and now in its second iteration, catalogues the new risks: prompt injection, training data poisoning, sensitive information disclosure, model denial of service, supply chain compromise.\n\nDefensive uses are equally significant but often misrepresented. Anomaly detection has been a research topic for decades, with mixed practical results — high false-positive rates have repeatedly turned promising prototypes into shelfware. Recent transformer-based approaches show better generalisation but still require careful baselining and ongoing tuning. The lesson, repeated across many evaluations, is that AI augments analysts rather than replacing them.\n\nThe regulatory frame is hardening. The EU AI Act of 2024 imposes obligations proportional to risk, with biometric identification systems and critical-infrastructure AI categorised as high-risk. The US AI Executive Order, the UK AI Safety Institute, and similar bodies in other jurisdictions impose evaluation requirements that are still maturing. Practitioners who recommend that organisations defer their AI security strategy until the regulation settles are increasingly out of step with the threat reality.\n\nFor systems engineers the practical answer is to treat AI components like any other untrusted dependency: with strong input validation, output sanitisation, monitoring, and incident response procedures designed for the failure modes of statistical systems.",
 "passage_wc":262,
 "source":"Adapted from OWASP Top 10 for LLMs (owasp.org, CC BY-SA), EU AI Act 2024 public summaries (europa.eu), US AI Executive Order 14110 (whitehouse.gov, PD)."},
12: {"topic":"Cloud security","grammar":"Nominal clauses",
 "notes_warmup":"Cloud is a different threat model. Most breaches are not cloud provider failures; they are customer misconfigurations of identity, storage, and networking.",
 "notes_rule":"Nominal clauses act as nouns: 'What we observed (subject) was alarming.' / 'The team agreed (object) that segmentation was urgent.'",
 "examples":[{"en":"What concerns auditors most is unmanaged identity sprawl.","note":"WHAT-clause as subject"}],
 "passage_title":"What goes wrong in the cloud",
 "passage_text":"The shared-responsibility model is well documented and routinely misunderstood. Major providers publish detailed matrices showing which controls they operate and which the customer must operate. Despite this clarity, the same misconfigurations recur across industries year after year: open storage buckets, over-permissive identity policies, exposed management interfaces, missing logging.\n\nIdentity is the new perimeter and the most common point of failure. The 2019 Capital One breach, in which a misconfigured web application firewall allowed an attacker to obtain credentials with excessive privileges, illustrated how a small identity error can produce a large data breach. The phrase 'identity is the new perimeter' has been overused to the point of cliché, but the underlying observation remains valid: in the cloud, what your identities can do matters far more than what your network looks like.\n\nMany of the dominant cloud-security tools — CSPM, CIEM, CNAPP, CWPP — exist precisely to surface these recurring problems. Cloud Security Posture Management continuously scans configurations against best-practice baselines. Cloud Infrastructure Entitlement Management focuses on identity sprawl: the gap between permissions granted and permissions actually used. Cloud-Native Application Protection Platforms attempt to integrate workload protection, posture management and identity governance into a single product, with mixed results in practice.\n\nThe consistent message from incident reports is that what matters most is operational discipline. The teams that maintain a clean cloud environment do so through automation: policy as code, infrastructure as code, continuous compliance pipelines. The teams that try to maintain a clean environment through manual review, however well-staffed they are, accumulate drift faster than they can fix it.",
 "passage_wc":262,
 "source":"Adapted from CISA cloud advisories (cisa.gov, PD), AWS Well-Architected Framework Security Pillar (aws.amazon.com), and the Capital One incident analysis (public)."},
13: {"topic":"DevSecOps","grammar":"Complex subordination",
 "notes_warmup":"DevSecOps is the integration of security into the delivery pipeline. The point is not 'shift left' as marketing slogan but feedback loops fast enough to influence behaviour.",
 "notes_rule":"Subordinate clauses combine to express layered ideas: time + cause + concession in the same sentence raise register without sacrificing clarity.",
 "examples":[{"en":"Although SAST has been available for two decades, its adoption has accelerated only since pipelines became fast enough to integrate it.","note":"concession + time"}],
 "passage_title":"DevSecOps in practice",
 "passage_text":"DevSecOps describes the practical integration of security into modern software-delivery pipelines. The conceptual ambition is straightforward: move security feedback close to the developer, where the cost of fixing a vulnerability is lowest. The execution, as ten years of public experience reports show, is harder than the slogan suggests.\n\nStatic analysis tools, often grouped under SAST, scan source code for unsafe patterns. The earliest commercial offerings produced more noise than signal; modern open-source tools like Semgrep have shifted the equation by allowing teams to write rules tailored to their codebase. Software Composition Analysis tracks third-party dependencies, comparing them against vulnerability databases and license obligations. The recent SBOM mandates from the US Executive Order 14028 have raised expectations: any product sold to the federal government must now ship with a software bill of materials, listing every dependency by version and identifier.\n\nDynamic analysis, abbreviated DAST, runs a deployed application and probes it for runtime vulnerabilities. Interactive analysis, IAST, instruments the application to combine the two perspectives. Although DAST has been available for as long as SAST, its integration into pipelines has lagged because dynamic tests take time and require running environments.\n\nSecret scanning is the highest-impact recent addition. Despite the universal advice never to commit secrets to source control, secrets continue to be committed at a steady rate. GitHub's secret-scanning service has prevented millions of credentials from going public; comparable features now exist on every major platform. The lesson, drawn from a decade of incidents, is that automation prevents what training alone cannot.",
 "passage_wc":255,
 "source":"Adapted from US Executive Order 14028 on Cybersecurity (whitehouse.gov, PD), CISA SBOM guidance (cisa.gov, PD), GitHub Security public docs."},
14: {"topic":"IoT security","grammar":"Discourse markers (formal)",
 "notes_warmup":"IoT brings the unmanaged-device problem to enterprise networks. The 'fridge that DDoSed the bank' is no longer a joke — it is a regulatory case study.",
 "notes_rule":"Formal discourse markers organise long arguments: 'Furthermore', 'In contrast', 'Notwithstanding this', 'On the other hand'. They go at the start of a sentence, with a comma.",
 "examples":[{"en":"Notwithstanding the regulation, default credentials persist in cheap devices.","note":"formal concession"}],
 "passage_title":"IoT security at the edge",
 "passage_text":"The number of connected devices on enterprise networks has surpassed the number of managed endpoints in many sectors. Hospitals operate connected medical equipment that runs unsupported operating systems. Manufacturing floors carry industrial controllers designed in an era when network exposure was unthinkable. Retail environments include cameras, point-of-sale terminals, and digital signage from dozens of vendors with widely varying security postures.\n\nThe Mirai botnet of 2016 was a wake-up call. Hundreds of thousands of cheap routers and IP cameras were compromised through default credentials and weaponised into the largest DDoS botnet of its era. Subsequent variants — Mozi, Aisuru, Dark Mirai — have continued to demonstrate that the underlying problem is structural rather than incidental.\n\nRegulators have begun to respond. The EU Cyber Resilience Act, adopted in late 2024, imposes baseline security obligations on connected products sold in the EU market. Manufacturers must support products throughout an explicit support window, publish vulnerability disclosure policies, and report exploited vulnerabilities to authorities within tight deadlines. The UK Product Security and Telecommunications Infrastructure Act and the US IoT Cybersecurity Improvement Act follow similar patterns.\n\nFor enterprises, the practical defence is segmentation. IoT devices belong on separate VLANs with strict outbound rules. Network detection and response tools that profile devices by behaviour have proven more useful than periodic vulnerability scans, because the devices themselves are often unscannable. Notwithstanding the regulation, default credentials persist in cheap devices for years; treating every IoT endpoint as untrusted by design remains the only durable approach.",
 "passage_wc":256,
 "source":"Adapted from CISA OT advisories (cisa.gov, PD), EU Cyber Resilience Act (europa.eu), Mirai botnet analysis (academic public)."},
15: {"topic":"Mobile security","grammar":"Inversion for emphasis",
 "notes_warmup":"Mobile is now the primary computing experience for most users. The threat model differs sharply from desktop: app stores, biometrics, MDM, jailbreak detection.",
 "notes_rule":"Inversion after restrictive adverbs raises register: 'Not only does iOS sandbox apps, it also enforces code signing.' 'Under no circumstances should jailbroken devices access corporate data.'",
 "examples":[{"en":"Rarely have mercenary spyware vendors faced consequences for end-use abuses.","note":"formal inversion"}],
 "passage_title":"Mobile threat models",
 "passage_text":"Modern mobile platforms have stronger default security than any desktop operating system. iOS combines hardware-rooted code signing, application sandboxing, and tightly controlled distribution through the App Store. Android, while more open, has converged on similar architectural protections: SELinux, Verified Boot, Play Protect. Both platforms have largely eliminated the kinds of vulnerabilities that defined desktop malware in the early 2000s.\n\nThe attacker's response has been to invest in highly targeted, often state-grade, exploit chains. Mercenary spyware vendors such as NSO Group, Cytrox, and Intellexa have repeatedly demonstrated zero-click iOS chains capable of compromising fully patched devices. The cost of these capabilities is high — millions of dollars per chain — but they are bought and used. Targeted journalists, dissidents, and human-rights defenders have been compromised in dozens of jurisdictions documented by Citizen Lab and Amnesty International.\n\nMobile Device Management is the enterprise control plane. MDM solutions enrol devices, enforce passcodes, manage app installation, and can wipe corporate data remotely. The friction with personal use is significant; the privacy concerns are legitimate. Modern MDM separates 'work' and 'personal' contexts to reduce the friction, particularly through Android Work Profiles and Apple's User Enrolment.\n\nUnder no circumstances should rooted or jailbroken devices be allowed to access corporate resources. Modern attestation primitives — Android Key Attestation, iOS DeviceCheck — let MDM verify device integrity cryptographically, which makes this a technical control rather than a policy hope.",
 "passage_wc":244,
 "source":"Adapted from Citizen Lab public research (citizenlab.ca, CC BY), OWASP Mobile Application Security (owasp.org, CC BY-SA), Apple Platform Security Guide (apple.com)."},
16: {"topic":"GDPR & data privacy","grammar":"Modal verbs in legal register",
 "notes_warmup":"GDPR was the watershed law that reshaped data protection globally. Five years on, fines have crossed the billion-euro mark, and similar regimes have proliferated across jurisdictions.",
 "notes_rule":"Legal English uses precise modals: SHALL = obligation, MAY = permission, MUST NOT = prohibition. Misusing them changes legal meaning.",
 "examples":[{"en":"The controller shall notify the supervisory authority within 72 hours.","note":"obligation"}],
 "passage_title":"GDPR and the global privacy patchwork",
 "passage_text":"The General Data Protection Regulation, in force since May 2018, restructured how organisations process the personal data of EU residents. Six lawful bases authorise processing — consent, contract, legal obligation, vital interests, public task, legitimate interests — each with its own evidentiary requirements. The regulation enshrined data subject rights including access, rectification, erasure, portability, and objection, all of which generate operational work for any organisation that holds significant personal data.\n\nFines have been substantial. Meta, Google, Amazon, and TikTok have each faced multi-hundred-million-euro penalties. The largest fines have been issued for cross-border transfer violations rather than for security incidents, illustrating that compliance with the international transfer rules — Standard Contractual Clauses, transfer impact assessments, the post-Schrems II adequacy framework — has been a primary regulatory focus.\n\nGlobally, similar regimes have proliferated. Brazil's LGPD, India's DPDP Act of 2023, China's PIPL, and a growing patchwork of US state laws — California, Virginia, Colorado, Connecticut and counting — each impose different obligations and have different relationships to GDPR. Multinational organisations have to operate compliance programmes that satisfy the strictest applicable rule and document the reasoning when interpretations differ.\n\nFor security teams, the practical implications are concrete. Breach notification timelines are tight: 72 hours under GDPR, sometimes shorter under sectoral regimes. Records of processing activities must be current. Data Protection Impact Assessments shall be conducted for high-risk processing. The intersection of legal obligation and engineering reality is permanent and demanding.",
 "passage_wc":250,
 "source":"Adapted from EU Regulation 2016/679 (europa.eu), EDPB guidelines (edpb.europa.eu), and CJEU Schrems II judgment public materials."},
17: {"topic":"Writing a security report","grammar":"Hedging language",
 "notes_warmup":"A great finding badly written gets ignored. A modest finding well written gets prioritised. The hedging language of professional reporting is what makes the difference.","notes_rule":"Hedge claims to signal uncertainty: 'appears to', 'is consistent with', 'with moderate confidence', 'likely / unlikely'. Confident absolutes are reserved for what you can prove.","examples":[{"en":"The activity is consistent with early-stage reconnaissance.","note":"hedge"}],
 "passage_title":"How a good security report reads",
 "passage_text":"A useful security report is a translation. The technical findings are the source language; business action is the target. Reports that fail this translation generate technical noise without organisational change.\n\nGood reports begin with an executive summary that fits on one page. The summary states the most important finding, its business impact, and the recommended action. Executives who read only the summary should walk away with the right priorities. Detailed technical findings follow, each with a consistent template: description, evidence, impact, likelihood, recommended remediation, and references.\n\nHedging language is essential. The temptation to overstate findings is real — researchers want their work to be noticed. The cost of overstating is also real: when a finding is described as 'critical' and the customer's investigation finds it to be moderate, all subsequent findings from the same author lose credibility. Mature reporting uses calibrated language: 'with high confidence', 'with moderate confidence', 'consistent with', 'cannot rule out'. The Intelligence Community Directive 203 provides the canonical reference for these distinctions, and increasingly commercial vendors adopt it.\n\nReproduction steps are non-negotiable. A finding without reproduction steps is closed without verification by sceptical engineers; a finding with clear steps is fixed and retested. Screenshots, request payloads, and tool versions all matter. CVSS and CWE references help defenders triage; without them, prioritisation across dozens of findings becomes guesswork.\n\nFinally, the relationship matters. The first report to a new customer sets the tone. Direct, evidence-based, calibrated language builds credibility that survives the inevitable disagreements about specific findings.",
 "passage_wc":262,
 "source":"Adapted from US ODNI ICD 203 Analytic Standards (odni.gov, PD), MITRE CWE (cwe.mitre.org), FIRST CVSS specifications (first.org)."},
18: {"topic":"Presenting security findings","grammar":"Rhetorical questions",
 "notes_warmup":"A presentation that loses the executive audience in the first ninety seconds is dead, no matter how good the findings. Pacing, structure and rhetorical questions matter.","notes_rule":"Rhetorical questions engage audiences and structure arguments: 'Why does this matter? Because…' 'What does this mean for us?'. They invite the listener to think.","examples":[{"en":"Why have we been compromised three times this year? Because we treated each as an isolated event.","note":"diagnostic"}],
 "passage_title":"Speaking to executives about security",
 "passage_text":"Communicating security findings to executives is a recognisable skill. Most analysts under-prepare for it. The patterns of failure are familiar: too much technical detail, too little business framing, charts that need explanation, and conclusions buried at the end.\n\nThe Pyramid Principle, popularised by Barbara Minto, applies directly. Lead with the conclusion. Support it with three reasons. Develop each reason with evidence. Audiences for whom time is the binding constraint absorb the conclusion in the first sentence and decide whether to listen for detail. Burying the conclusion in the last slide treats their time as cheap, which they will notice.\n\nRhetorical questions provide structure without sounding lecture-like. Why have ransomware attacks against our sector tripled this year? What is the cost of a single ransomware incident at our scale? What investments would change our exposure? Each question opens a section the speaker then answers. The audience is mentally engaged; the structure is transparent.\n\nNumbers belong in stories, not in tables. 'Forty-two phishing attempts succeeded last quarter' lands harder than a heatmap. Stories illustrate impact. The hospital that paid ransom and still lost patient data; the manufacturing line that could not resume for fourteen days; the CISO who escalated four months before the breach but was not heard. These narratives support the technical evidence.\n\nFinally, ask for the decision. Vague briefings end with discussion; effective ones end with a clear ask: a budget figure, a policy change, a hire, a new programme. Without an explicit decision, the message dissolves on the way back to operations.",
 "passage_wc":268,
 "source":"Adapted from Barbara Minto, 'The Pyramid Principle' (well-known summaries), Verizon DBIR public reports (verizon.com/dbir)."},
19: {"topic":"Debate: privacy vs security","grammar":"Concession and counter-argument",
 "notes_warmup":"Privacy and security are often framed as opposed. They sometimes are. Mature professionals can argue all three positions: trade-off, complement, false dichotomy.","notes_rule":"Build balanced argument with concession structures: 'Granted, X. Nevertheless, Y.' 'Although X, Y nevertheless.' 'It is true that X. That said, Y.'","examples":[{"en":"Granted, end-to-end encryption complicates investigations. Nevertheless, weakening it would expose ordinary users.","note":"concession"}],
 "passage_title":"The privacy-security debate revisited",
 "passage_text":"The debate between privacy and security is older than the internet. The post-9/11 era reframed it sharply: governments argued for expanded surveillance powers; civil-society organisations argued for cryptographic protections. Two decades on, the lines have blurred without settling.\n\nThe Apple-FBI dispute of 2016 illustrated the tension. The FBI demanded that Apple build a way to bypass the lock screen of an iPhone used by a terrorist. Apple refused, arguing that any backdoor would inevitably leak and be exploited against ordinary users. The case was settled when an external vendor — reportedly the Australian firm Azimuth Security — broke the device. The underlying question was never resolved.\n\nClient-side scanning revived the debate in the early 2020s. Apple announced and then suspended a system to scan iCloud Photos for known child sexual abuse material before encryption. Civil society organisations argued that the architecture, regardless of intent, normalised local surveillance. Apple's eventual retreat was widely seen as a concession to that argument.\n\nThe European debate has shifted with the proposed CSAM regulation, often called 'Chat Control' by critics. The proposal would require platforms to detect known and new CSAM in encrypted communications. Granted, the policy goal is unobjectionable. Nevertheless, no technology currently exists that detects content in encrypted streams without breaking the encryption properties on which all secure communication depends. The debate continues at the time of writing.\n\nThe systems engineer is rarely empowered to settle these debates. They can, however, refuse to participate in technically incoherent designs.",
 "passage_wc":256,
 "source":"Adapted from Apple-FBI public filings, EFF analysis of CSAM regulation (eff.org, CC BY), and Citizen Lab public commentary."},
20: {"topic":"Mock FCE + B2 portfolio","grammar":"B2 grammar recap",
 "notes_warmup":"You are ready for B2 First. The exam is integrated, and the gap between failure and a high pass is mostly attention to detail in Use of English and tight Writing.","notes_rule":"B2 brings together: mixed conditionals, cleft sentences, concession (despite/although/however), inversion, participle clauses, passive reporting.","examples":[{"en":"Had we segmented earlier, the breach would not have spread.","note":"3rd conditional inversion"}],
 "passage_title":"Reflecting on the B2 journey",
 "passage_text":"Eighteen months ago I started this programme as a junior systems engineer with intermediate English. My professional reading was limited to short articles; I avoided meetings in English when I could; I rewrote emails three times and still felt unsure. Today, I read IEEE Spectrum casually, run sprint planning in English with engineers in three time zones, and have just submitted my first technical paper for internal review.\n\nThe progress has been less linear than I expected. Use of English was the unexpected bottleneck. Vocabulary I could grow with discipline. Listening improved with consistent exposure. Writing improved with feedback. The Use of English transformations and word formations, however, required the kind of structured grammar work that I had been avoiding since school. Once I committed to thirty minutes a day on transformations alone, the rest accelerated noticeably.\n\nWriting is where I expect the biggest demand at work. The structures I learned to use deliberately — cleft sentences, concessive linkers, hedging language — have changed how my reports read. A senior colleague told me recently that I now sound like a different writer. I take that as evidence the programme worked.\n\nLooking forward, my plan is to take the B2 First exam in eight weeks, then move to C1 Advanced over the next year. I want to lead a major migration project in English by 2027 and present at an international conference by 2028. Had I been told three years ago that I would write this paragraph in English, I would not have believed it.",
 "passage_wc":253,
 "source":"Original. Reflective essay format consistent with Cambridge B2 First Writing Part 1."}
}

